<p>In the future, the Army's role in CWMD will continue to grow, and the Army will lead and execute CWMD missions focused on operations that prevent the use of WMD.  The focus of CWMD shifts from post-use (right of boom) Consequence Management to pre-use (left of boom) denial.</p>
<p>In support of this, ARCIC has initiated multiple efforts that will identify required capabilities for both the current and future forces to execute all CWMD functions.  The MSPD, Requirements Integration Division (RID), completed a Radiological and Nuclear Interdiction (RNI) DOTMLPF Policy (DOTMLPF-P) study in November of 2012 that focused on the Conventional Force (CF) ability to detect and interdict RN materials.  Additionally, MSPD will complete a similar study by February of 2014 that will assess CF capability to detect and interdict chemical materials.</p>
